\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\qc\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 -o-}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {The hands clamped on Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s arms weren\u8217\'92t painful, but they were firm, unyielding. A wall of muscle flanked him on either side, their matching Student Council armbands stark against their dark jackets. They marched him down the silent, echoing corridors of the Alchemy Faculty building, his recently healed ankle feeling fine but offering no chance of a successful escape. He\u8217\'92d been so close. A few more minutes with Hudson\u8217\'92s files and he might have found something. Instead, he\u8217\'92d found them.}
\par\plain {He tried for a disarming grin, a tactic that rarely worked but was better than silence.}
\par\plain {"Come on, guys," Eddie said, his voice echoing slightly in the empty hall. "How do you know I was snooping around the professor\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s office? How do you know that maybe Professor Hudson didn't just send me to his office to fetch him the stuff he forgot?"}
\par\plain {The council member on his right, a boy with a neck as thick as a tree trunk, didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t even look at him. "You are not his lecture assistant," he said, his voice a flat monotone. "You shouldn't have access to his office to begin with."}
\par\plain {"Well, I know, I know," Eddie pressed on, trying to keep his tone light. "But what if I'm his favourite student? Shouldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t you think I have access then?"}
\par\plain {"It doesn't matter," said the one on the left. "You broke curfew, and you were in a place where you don't belong."}
\par\plain {The first one added the final nail to the coffin. "And also, you are Edward Welton." The way he said the name made it sound like a pre-existing condition. "This is your third warning. Your last warning." He steered Eddie toward the grand staircase leading to the administrative wing. "Victoria wants to see you."}
\par\plain {Eddie let out a sigh, the fight draining out of him. Victoria Aynesworth, head of the Student Council and a stickler for rules so rigid they made Hudson look laid-back. This was bad.}
\par\plain {"Oh, great," he muttered, then added with a layer of sarcasm thick enough to cut with a knife, "Can't wait to see her."}
\par\plain {The two students marched him up the grand staircase and down a corridor lined with portraits of past university deans whose painted eyes seemed to follow him with stern disapproval. They stopped before a set of imposing double doors carved from dark oak. One of the guards pushed a door open, revealing the Student Council room.}
\par\plain {It looked less like an office and more like a judge\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s private chambers. A vaulted ceiling disappeared into shadows high above, the walls were lined with dark wood paneling, and the air was still and cold. A single, massive desk stood on a raised dais at the far end of the room, stark and empty. It didn\u8217\'92t surprise Eddie in the slightest.}
\par\plain {He was guided to a lone wooden chair positioned in the center of the floor and sat down, the guards retreating to stand impassively by the door. It was well past midnight; he hadn't expected anyone to be here, least of all the Council Head herself. He was wrong.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Where did you find him this time?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The voice was sharp, cutting through the silence from the shadowed corner of the room. It was Victoria.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The Professor's room,\u8221\'94 the guard on the right reported, his voice flat. \u8220\'93He was caught going through Professor Gareth Hudson's personal files.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93And the two others?\u8221\'94 Victoria\u8217\'92s voice was coolly analytical. \u8220\'93Have you checked? He never goes alone.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93I was alone this time.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s voice cut across the room, firm and clear, startling the guard who had begun to answer. He didn't look at them; he stared directly into the shadows where she was hidden. \u8220\'93You don\u8217\'92t have to worry about Will and Ashley. I went alone.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {A beat of silence hung in the cavernous room. Then, the sound began\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 the sharp, deliberate clack of heels against the cold stone floor. A figure started to emerge from the darkness, moving with unhurried purpose. As she stepped into the faint light spilling from the hallway, her form was revealed.}
\par\plain {She was dressed in a dark tweed blazer over a pristine collared shirt and a pleated skirt that fell exactly to her knees. Her blonde hair was pulled back in a severe, intricate braid, not a single strand out of place. She was posh, precise, and carried an air of authority that made the two brutes by the door seem like mere decoration.}
\par\plain {She stopped a few feet in front of his chair, her gaze level and unnervingly direct.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93So,\u8221\'94 she said, a faint, unreadable smile touching her lips. \u8220\'93Edward Welton, isn\u8217\'92t it? I\u8217\'92m glad we finally met.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Victoria\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s gaze was sharp, analytical, as if she were examining a particularly curious but troublesome specimen. One of the guards by the door stepped forward, his shadow falling over Eddie.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Your phone and staff,\u8221\'94 the guard said, his voice a low rumble. He gestured to a small, empty table across the room. \u8220\'93On the table. Now.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Eddie\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s jaw tightened. They were disarming him. It was a clear message: they knew he was more than just a common rule-breaker. With a defiant slowness, he reached into his jacket, pulled out the collapsible length of his alchemy staff and the sleek black rectangle of his phone, and walked them over to the designated table. The click of the staff settling on the polished wood sounded unnervingly final. He returned to his chair feeling distinctly more vulnerable.}
\par\plain {As he sat, Victoria began to move, her heels making sharp, deliberate clicks on the stone floor as she started to circle him. In her hands, she held a clipboard, a single sheet of paper clipped neatly to its surface.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92ve become something of a celebrity this term, Welton,\u8221\'94 she said, her voice a cool, even tone that offered no hint of her thoughts. \u8220\'93A recurring topic of discussion in our weekly disciplinary meetings.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {She paused behind him, forcing him to sit rigidly still, every nerve on edge.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Let\u8217\'92s review, shall we?\u8221\'94 she continued, the rustle of the paper unnaturally loud in the silence. \u8220\'93First, there was the incident in the main library after curfew. A simple warning.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Her footsteps continued their measured circuit.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then, the unauthorized removal of a text from the restricted section. A second, more severe warning.\u8221\'94 She stopped in his peripheral vision, tapping the paper with a perfectly manicured nail. \u8220\'93And now tonight. Breaking into a professor\u8217\'92s private office and going through his personal files.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {She completed her circle, coming to a stop in front of him once more. She lowered the clipboard, her gaze finally locking onto his.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Looking at this record,\u8221\'94 she said, her tone laced with a kind of detached curiosity, \u8220\'93a clear pattern of escalation\u8230\'85 I find myself wondering, Welton. I wonder why I haven't simply forwarded this to the Faculty Dean and been done with it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {The question hung in the air, a threat veiled as a musing. Eddie swallowed, his mind racing for an excuse, a plausible lie\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 anything.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Look,\u8221\'94 he started, trying to sound reasonable. \u8220\'93It was a simple mistake. Professor Hudson asked me to fetch a book from his office. He\u8217\'92d forgotten it.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Victoria didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t even blink. She flipped a page on her clipboard with a soft rustle. \u8220\'93Professor Hudson began a three-day personal leave this evening. An official notice was posted.\u8221\'94 She looked up at him, her eyes cold and dissecting. \u8220\'93If you\u8217\'92re going to lie, Welton, you should at least study your subject before speaking.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {He felt his face flush, his excuse crumbling into dust. He opened his mouth to conjure something else, anything else, but she cut him off with a raised hand.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Before you invent another fabrication,\u8221\'94 she said, her tone shifting from condescending to severe, \u8220\'93let\u8217\'92s discuss a more serious matter. It\u8217\'92s come to my attention that you\u8217\'92ve been contacting local political groups within Edenfield, trying to acquire information.\u8221\'94 She paused, letting the weight of the new accusation land. \u8220\'93This is strictly forbidden. Students are permitted to join university advocacy groups. Contact with external political bodies is prohibited to avoid conflicts of interest with the Crown. You know this.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {This time, Eddie didn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t lie. The truth came out, raw and urgent. \u8220\'93Because there is something happening in this city! Something wrong. And I am trying to find out what the hell is going on before something worse happens!\u8221\'94}
